      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/sqa-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA criteria for MRL 5 CFD hemolysis solver",
        "description": "The CFD solver must have a documented QA plan including version control, regression test suite with >95% pass rate, and traceable build records. All third-party libraries must carry documented validation status. Achieved: solver QA plan reviewed and confirmed compliant; regression suite passed 98% of 450 test cases."
      },
      "rationale": "The hemolysis CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9 with custom hemolysis transport module) operates under a documented software quality assurance plan. Version control via Git with tagged releases, automated regression testing (450 cases, 98% pass rate), and traceable build logs satisfy MRL 5 SQA requirements at Gradation 4."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ncv",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/ncv-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Manufactured solution tests (method of manufactured solutions, MMS) must demonstrate expected order of convergence (±10% of theoretical) for all governing equations including hemolysis transport. Achieved: MMS studies confirm second-order spatial accuracy for momentum and scalar transport; hemolysis source term verified against analytical benchmark."
      },
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions applied to the full Navier-Stokes plus hemolysis scalar transport system. Observed convergence rates of 1.96 (momentum) and 1.98 (hemolysis scalar) are within 2% of theoretical second-order, satisfying Gradation 4 numerical code verification requirements at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/disc-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/disc-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error criteria for MRL 5 pump CFD",
        "description": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be computed on three systematically refined meshes (refinement ratio ≥1.3) and reported for hemolysis index and wall shear stress. GCI on fine mesh must be <5% for hemolysis index QoI. Achieved: three-mesh GCI study yields GCI_fine = 2.8% for hemolysis index at design point."
      },
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on the FDA centrifugal pump geometry (coarse: 2.1M cells, medium: 5.8M cells, fine: 16.2M cells; refinement ratio 1.41). GCI on fine mesh is 2.8% for the hemolysis index QoI and 3.1% for peak wall shear stress, both below the 5% acceptance threshold. Apparent order of convergence p=1.94 confirms asymptotic regime."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-conditions-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions fidelity criteria for VAD hemolysis validation",
        "description": "Experimental test conditions (hematocrit, temperature, flow rate, rotational speed) must be documented with measurement uncertainty and replicated in CFD boundary conditions within stated tolerances. Achieved: all five operating points reproduced with flow rate within ±2% and rotational speed within ±0.5%."
      },
      "rationale": "FDA pump hemolysis experiments conducted at five operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) with bovine blood at 37°C and hematocrit 33±2%. CFD boundary conditions replicate experimental inlet velocity profiles (measured via LDV) and rotational speed with documented uncertainty budgets. Test condition fidelity satisfies Gradation 3 at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/output-comparison-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison criteria for absolute hemolysis prediction",
        "description": "Predicted hemolysis index (MIH, mg/dL) must agree with experimental measurements within combined simulation and experimental uncertainty intervals at all five operating points. U95 validation metric must be within model uncertainty band. Achieved: all five operating points satisfy U95 coverage; mean absolute error 8.3% of experimental mean."
      },
      "rationale": "Absolute hemolysis index predictions compared against FDA pump experimental measurements at all five operating points. Mean absolute percentage error is 8.3%; all predictions fall within the combined U95 uncertainty band (simulation uncertainty from Monte Carlo ensemble plus experimental measurement uncertainty). Validation metric satisfies Gradation 4 for output comparison at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/qoi-relevance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance criteria for VAD hemolysis COU",
        "description": "The primary QoI (modified index of hemolysis, MIH) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint (plasma-free hemoglobin) and must be the same metric used in the regulatory submission threshold. Achieved: MIH is the FDA-accepted hemolysis metric; direct mapping to clinical threshold documented in the assessment plan."
      },
      "rationale": "The modified index of hemolysis (MIH, mg/dL) is the primary QoI and is directly mapped to the FDA-accepted clinical hemolysis threshold for VAD devices. The QoI is identical to the metric used in predicate device submissions, ensuring direct regulatory relevance. Gradation 4 achieved for QoI relevance at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/validation-relevance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance criteria for COU2",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump), same operating envelope (flow rates and speeds spanning the COU), and same blood analogue or bovine blood with documented rheology. Achieved: FDA pump geometry used; all five COU operating points covered by validation experiments."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation activities use the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the same geometry as the COU device surrogate. All five COU operating points (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM) are covered by validation experiments. Blood analogue rheology is matched to bovine blood with documented viscosity and density. Validation relevance satisfies Gradation 4 at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped out because the hemolysis CFD solver (OpenFOAM v9) is an open-source code with a large body of published verification studies. Solver-level floating-point and iterative convergence errors are bounded by the numerical code verification (MMS) and discretization error (GCI) factors assessed above. Separate solver error quantification would be redundant at MRL 5 given the comprehensive code verification evidence already in the package."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out because all CFD simulations are executed by a single trained analyst team following a documented simulation execution procedure (SEP) with mandatory peer review of setup files prior to each run. The SEP includes checklist verification of boundary conditions, mesh quality metrics, and solver settings. Under this controlled execution protocol, undetected user-induced errors are considered negligible at the MRL 5 risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty is scoped out of this credibility factor assessment because it is subsumed by the output comparison factor: the validation metric directly captures aggregate model form error relative to experimental data at all five operating points. Separate model form uncertainty quantification via model-form sensitivity studies is deferred to a follow-on MRL 5+ assessment; the current evidence base does not support independent model-form factor scoring without double-counting the validation comparison evidence."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs uncertainty criteria for VAD CFD",
        "description": "All uncertain model inputs (blood viscosity, hemolysis power-law exponent, inlet velocity profile) must be characterised with probability distributions derived from literature or experiment, and propagated through the model via Monte Carlo sampling (≥500 samples). Achieved: 1000-sample Monte Carlo ensemble completed; input PDFs documented."
      },
      "rationale": "Six uncertain model inputs identified: blood dynamic viscosity (Carreau model parameters), hemolysis power-law exponent C and α, inlet velocity profile shape, and rotational speed. Probability distributions derived from published experimental data. 1000-sample Monte Carlo ensemble propagated through the CFD model; output uncertainty bands reported at 95% confidence. Gradation 3 achieved for model inputs at MRL 5."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test samples factor is scoped out because the FDA generic centrifugal pump is a fixed-geometry reference device; there is no manufacturing variability in the test article. All experimental hemolysis measurements were performed on a single precision-machined pump specimen whose geometry was laser-scanned and confirmed to match the nominal CAD within 50 µm. Sample-to-sample geometric variability is therefore not a credibility concern for this COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equiv-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is scoped out because the validation case and the COU use identical input parameter sets: the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, the same five operating points, and the same blood rheology model. There is no extrapolation of input parameters from the validation domain to the COU domain. Equivalency is therefore structurally guaranteed by study design, and a separate credibility factor assessment would add no discriminating information."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou2-vad-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/org/morrison-vv40-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The CFD hemolysis model for the FDA generic centrifugal pump under VAD conditions is accepted as credible for the COU2 intended use (absolute hemolysis index prediction, Class III, MRL 5). Seven credibility factors were formally assessed: all seven achieved required gradation levels (SQA: 4/4, Numerical code verification: 4/4, Discretization error: 4/4, Test conditions: 3/3, Output comparison: 4/4, QoI relevance: 4/4, Validation relevance: 4/4, Model inputs: 3/3 — note: eight factors assessed, not seven). Six factors were scoped out with documented rationale: numerical solver error (subsumed by NCV and GCI), use error (controlled execution protocol), model form (subsumed by output comparison), test samples (single reference geometry), and equivalency of input parameters (structurally guaranteed by study design). The 1000-sample Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification confirms that absolute hemolysis index predictions fall within the combined simulation-experimental uncertainty band at all five operating points (mean absolute error 8.3%). The provenance chain is complete from raw experimental data through CFD ensemble to validation results. No credibility factor gaps remain. The model is fit for the stated purpose of supporting regulatory submission for absolute hemolysis acceptance of a Class III VAD device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
